# PC & Laboratory Identification — Deep Plan

## The Core Problem

Same hostname (e.g., `PC1`) exists in multiple labs. So `PC1` alone is **ambiguous** — is it `PC1` in Lab 1 or `PC1` in Lab 2?

We need a **second piece of information** to identify the lab. That second piece lives in the **network** — specifically, in the router/switch the PC is connected to.

---

## How Campus Networks Work (Your Setup)

```
INTERNET
    │
 Main Router (campus)
    ├── Switch/Router for Laboratory 1  → gateway: 192.168.1.1  → subnet: 192.168.1.x
    │       ├── PC1  (192.168.1.11)
    │       ├── PC2  (192.168.1.12)
    │       └── PC3  (192.168.1.13)
    │
    ├── Switch/Router for Laboratory 2  → gateway: 192.168.2.1  → subnet: 192.168.2.x
    │       ├── PC1  (192.168.2.11)
    │       ├── PC2  (192.168.2.12)
    │       └── PC3  (192.168.2.13)
    │
    └── Switch/Router for Laboratory 3  → gateway: 192.168.3.1  → subnet: 192.168.3.x
            └── ...
```

Each lab has its own **switch/router with a different IP range (subnet)**. This is the standard campus setup.

### The Key Insight

Every PC knows:
1. Its own **hostname** → `PC1` (configured in Windows Settings)
2. Its own **IP address** → e.g., `192.168.2.11`
3. Its **gateway (router) IP** → e.g., `192.168.2.1` ← **This identifies the lab!**

So: **Gateway IP `192.168.2.1` = Laboratory 2**

Combined identifier: `hostname` + `gateway IP` → `PC1 — Laboratory 2`

---

## The Two-Table Database Design

We need **two separate mappings**:

### Table 1: `lab_gateways` *(NEW)*
Maps gateway IP to a laboratory room name.

| id | gateway_ip | laboratory_room |
|----|-----------|-----------------|
| 1 | 192.168.1.1 | Laboratory 1 |
| 2 | 192.168.2.1 | Laboratory 2 |
| 3 | 192.168.3.1 | Laboratory 3 |

Admin adds one entry per laboratory. This never changes unless the IT team reconfigures the network.

### Table 2: `lab_computers` *(existing — needs schema change)*
Maps hostname to a human-readable display name, **per lab** (not globally unique).

Current unique constraint: `computer_name` must be globally unique ❌ → **Wrong for your case**

New design: unique constraint on [(hostname, laboratory_room)](file:///c:/Users/ranie/OneDrive/Desktop/Sia-Web/Backend-Laravel/app/Http/Controllers/Api/AuthController.php#101-175). This enforces your exact rule:
- `PC1` in `Laboratory 1` ✅
- `PC1` in `Laboratory 2` ✅ (Same hostname, different lab)
- `PC1` in `Laboratory 1` second time ❌ (Not allowed: same hostname in SAME lab)

| id | hostname | display_name | laboratory_room |
|----|----------|-------------|-----------------|
| 1 | PC1 | PC 1 | Laboratory 1 |
| 2 | PC2 | PC 2 | Laboratory 1 |
| 3 | PC1 | PC 1 | Laboratory 2 |
| 4 | PC2 | PC 2 | Laboratory 2 |

> [!NOTE]
> `display_name` is optional — it can just mirror `hostname` or be a friendly alias like "PC Near Window". Admin can customize.

### Monitoring Sessions *(existing — minor change)*
Add `gateway_ip` column alongside the existing `computer_name` column so we always know **both** pieces:

| student_user_id | computer_name | gateway_ip | laboratory_room (resolved) |
|---|---|---|---|
| 5 | PC1 | 192.168.2.1 | Laboratory 2 |
| 8 | PC1 | 192.168.1.1 | Laboratory 1 |

